    <div class="post-container" id="fpc-2055951">
                      
		<div class="post" id="post-2055951">
		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,2055951)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-2055951">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser deleted" data-id="1324229"><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/common--images/avatars/default/a16.png" alt=""/>(account deleted)</span> <span class="odate time_1403383307 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">21 Jun 2014 20:41</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2055951">
									

<p>I can't help but feel disappointed about this. It's not that it's bad; far from it. It's just that I was expecting <em>more</em>. I had pictured something more akin to <a href="http://www.vinmag.com/online/media/gbu0/prodxl/AP520-barnum-bailey-circus-poster-1912.jpg">old-fashioned circus posters</a> with anomalous hand monsters and flame-engulfed men. Obviously, this would be impractical because a) the requirement that the &quot;documents&quot; be easily replicable b) this is an amateur writing site, rather than a professional graphic design sign. The use of minimal text to mimic it produces mixed results. Still, while this evokes some of the sense of wonder that seems to have been part and parcel of these things (thirding the FL comparison), I wish that there was <em>more</em>. If not graphically, at least in terms of writing.</p>
<p>This isn't a problem with the article as such, just a complaint about what I feel is unrealized potential. The article itself is good enough for an upvote, to be sure.</p>

							</div>

								
